As the white petals finally dissolved, they did not fall to the dark earth. Instead, they took flight on gossamer wings, their bell-like shapes transforming into tiny, glowing bodies. These were the very first fireflies. Born from the fading snowdrops and the warmth of the sun, they scattered into the twilight. Now, long after the snow has melted, these gentle lights dance through the humid summer nights, a lingering memory of the delicate white bells that once bridged the turning seasons.

