Myth: Throughout the long, humid summer, the fireflies danced through the ancient woods, their tiny lights a joyful memory of the elusive fire foxes. But as the wheel of the year turned once more, a crisp autumn chill crept into the twilight air. The nights grew longer, and the gentle, flickering beacons of the fireflies began to fade against the biting wind.

Knowing their fragile wings could not survive the impending frost, the fireflies sought refuge high in the canopy of the great oak trees. They settled gently upon the broad green leaves, pouring the last of their golden summer magic into the foliage. Instantly, the leaves were set ablaze with brilliant hues of crimson, orange, and gold, capturing the warmth of the fireflies' fading embers.

When the autumn winds finally ripped the leaves from their branches, they fluttered to the damp forest floor. Where each glowing leaf landed, the earth absorbed the residual spark. Overnight, tiny, luminescent mushrooms sprouted from the soil. These were the first foxfire fungi. Glowing with a soft, eerie light, they illuminate the dark autumn woods, guiding nocturnal creatures safely through the shadows and keeping the fading memory of summer alive until the snow returns.
